The map is enclosed in a single, heavily fortified border befitting the city of outlaws. Its outermost edge is a hairline of rusted, blood‑brown iron, pitted and sharp. Inside runs a continuous register of stylised, overlapping security tape, chain‑link fences, and jagged wanted‑poster motifs, rendered in raised, matte black and sepia lacquer. The posters feature tiny, ghosted ink portraits of the city’s most wanted. At the four corners, the border transforms into ornate, noir compass medallions: a cracked desert skull with a golden tooth (northwest), a crossed pair of ornate revolvers (northeast), a heavy‑locked vault door (southwest), and a single, glowing violet crystal shard (southeast). The innermost edge is a rough, heavy enso circle of gritty charcoal sumi, its stroke deliberately smudged, like a fingerprint — a meditation on the blurred line between law and survival.

5. THE LANDSCAPE — ZOOMED‑IN, HYPER‑DETAILED LOS PECADOS
The city and its immediate surroundings are a breathtaking, suffocating tapestry of vertical slums, opulent hidden halls, and the ever‑present watch of the King.

The Canyon Walls & The Main Gulch: The city is built into a deep, shadowy gulch, its walls towering and striated with layers of red and ochre rock. The main entrance is the Throat, a narrow canyon pass guarded by makeshift watchtowers. The bottom of the gulch is a dusty, chaotic sprawl of market stalls, cantinas, and body shops.

The Plaza of Shattered Hopes: The central public space is the Plaza of Shattered Hopes, a wide, cracked flagstone square dominated by a dry fountain that hasn’t seen water in decades. It is surrounded by low adobe buildings with corrugated iron roofs and flickering neon signs. Tiny, dueling outlaw silhouettes are frozen mid‑fight, while other figures trade stolen goods.

The Vault of the Gilded Shadow (Alistair Vane’s Tower): On the highest, most defensible mesa overlooking the gulch, stands the Vault of the Gilded Shadow, the private sanctum of the Thief King. It is a low, brutalist fortress of reinforced steel and black glass, almost invisible against the rock. Its upper floor is a single, expansive office with a massive, one‑way window.

Alistair Vane — The Thief King (Tiny, Commanding Silhouette): Visible through that enormous window, rendered with exquisite precision despite his tiny scale, is Alistair Vane himself. He is not standing; he is seated in a high‑backed leather chair, his figure a study in quiet, absolute authority. His heavy, floor‑length midnight‑violet overcoat is draped over his shoulders, not worn through the sleeves. His raven‑black hair is pulled back into a meticulous low ponytail, a few silver strands at his temple catching the faint, cold light from his holographic screens. His left hand rests on the arm of the chair; his right hand grips the ebony shaft of the Midas Touch, his five‑foot cane, its handle a golden‑bronze clenched fist clutching a single, pulsing violet energy crystal. The crystal glows with a rhythmic, heartbeat‑like pulse. Beside his chair, a faint, almost invisible holographic decoy flickers — a second, identical seated figure, half‑real.

The Den of the Lost (Claude & Dexter’s Haunt): On a lower, more chaotic rooftop near the market, a tiny, distinct silhouette of Claude can be seen. He is not stationary; he is caught mid‑stride, one hand holding an oversized golden‑bronze hand‑cannon, his teal tunic and vibrant magenta scarf a sudden burst of colour in the dusty palette. At his side, the tiny, four‑legged silhouette of Dexter, his monkey companion, clings to his leg, wearing miniature aviator goggles. They are ghosts of the city’s past, a reminder of the family the Thief King built and betrayed.

The Neon‑Lit Under‑Market: The lower right quadrant of the city is the Neon‑Lit Under‑Market, a warren of stalls selling black‑market cybernetics and illegal mana shards. Glowing, stuttering cyan and magenta holo‑signs cast their light onto the dusty ground. Tiny, hooded smuggler silhouettes haggle over crates.

