The map is enclosed in a single, ancient, death‑kissed border befitting the tomb of the Desert Tyrant. Its outermost edge is a hairline of tarnished, sand‑scoured gold, dull and heavy. Inside runs a continuous register of stylised, swirling sand‑dune motifs and the coiling forms of ancient, hieroglyph‑etched bandages, rendered in raised, matte ochre and pale, glowing teal lacquer. The bandages seem to weave in and out of the dunes, binding the border together. At the four corners, the border transforms into ornate, mortuary compass medallions: a golden death‑mask of a pharaoh (northwest), a sarcophagus sealed with the double crown of Upper and Lower Agelta (northeast), a crossed crook and flail bound in teal bandages (southwest), and a single, weeping, amber‑glowing eye (southeast). The innermost edge is a dry, cracked enso circle of charcoal‑and‑sand sumi, its stroke heavy and fractured, as if drawn with a brittle, ancient brush — a meditation on the weight of a lost kingdom, the madness of the sands, and the eternal, tyrannical hunger of the undead.

